10:53.679 --> 10:58.136
♪♪♪

10:58.220 --> 11:01.845
Attorney General Rhoades, we'd
like to discuss our assignment.

11:01.929 --> 11:03.804
Please, come in.

11:10.428 --> 11:14.428
We have a problem with
the assignment, sir--

11:14.512 --> 11:16.804
well, an ethical
objection, really.

11:16.887 --> 11:18.762
I see.

11:18.845 --> 11:21.720
Please, explain, Merle.

11:21.804 --> 11:23.387
[Merle] We're concerned
that the process

11:23.470 --> 11:26.053
you've asked us to follow
feels, like...

11:26.136 --> 11:27.720
improperly motivated.

11:27.804 --> 11:29.804
[Dee Dee] It's backwards.

11:29.887 --> 11:32.970
To just try and find something
on Secretary Krakow.

11:33.053 --> 11:36.970
Aren't we supposed to start with
a crime and then build a case?

11:37.053 --> 11:38.595
It feels
super targeted.

11:38.679 --> 11:41.970
Like the Muslim ban
or something.

11:44.845 --> 11:48.428
You have been very fortunate
in your short lives

11:48.512 --> 11:49.970
to read the sharpest
legal scholars

11:50.053 --> 11:52.220
and discuss the most
famous cases.

11:52.303 --> 11:56.178
But [chuckles]
you have never

11:56.261 --> 12:00.095
stood naked before
judge or jury.

12:00.178 --> 12:04.345
You have never made a single
compromise of conscience.

12:04.428 --> 12:09.095
You have never had to weigh
justice against loyalty...

12:11.428 --> 12:15.512
You know, lawyers are,
importantly, storytellers.

12:15.595 --> 12:18.345
So allow me to
weave you a yarn.

12:18.428 --> 12:21.762
[clears throat]
An old folktale goes:

12:21.845 --> 12:26.553
A Sicilian woman and
an Arab trader fell in love.

12:26.637 --> 12:30.136
But the Arab had a wife
and children back in Tunisia.

12:30.220 --> 12:33.720
So he told the Sicilian woman
that he loved her,

12:33.804 --> 12:35.595
but he had to go back
to his family.

12:35.679 --> 12:38.470
That night,
the Sicilian woman

12:38.553 --> 12:42.261
cut off his head
while he was sleeping.

12:42.345 --> 12:43.804
She hollowed out his brains,

12:43.887 --> 12:46.887
and she turned his skull
into a pot,

12:46.970 --> 12:48.887
where she planted herbs.

12:48.970 --> 12:50.887
[chuckles]

12:50.970 --> 12:52.970
And you can still
see ceramic pots

12:53.053 --> 12:56.845
painted like Arab heads
in Palermo today.

12:56.929 --> 12:59.929
There are several lessons
that can be taken

13:00.011 --> 13:01.512
from this grisly
tale of passion,

13:01.595 --> 13:03.470
but the one I draw is this:

13:03.553 --> 13:05.470
If you harbor
split loyalties,

13:05.553 --> 13:07.220
and fail to take a side,

13:07.303 --> 13:08.970
your mind may become
nothing more

13:09.053 --> 13:12.178
than the soil
for mint sprigs.

13:12.261 --> 13:14.804
If you have any doubts
about your ability

13:14.887 --> 13:16.178
to complete this internship

13:16.261 --> 13:18.720
or your allegiance
to this office,

13:18.804 --> 13:20.929
leave now.

13:31.011 --> 13:33.178
Anybody else?

13:33.261 --> 13:34.845
No way.

13:34.929 --> 13:36.261
Good.

13:36.345 --> 13:38.303
Now let's get back to it.

13:46.470 --> 13:49.387
Do you still have any contacts
in the Treasury Department?

13:49.470 --> 13:52.553
I was in the Katzenjammers with
the Deputy Assistant Secretary.

13:52.637 --> 13:54.929
Did I know you could
carry a tune, Ms. Sacker?

13:55.011 --> 13:57.095
What can't I do?
Good.

13:57.178 --> 14:00.345
Then I'd like to see
Krakow's schedule of meetings.

14:00.428 --> 14:02.095
Maybe there's a buzzsaw
we can run him into.

14:02.178 --> 14:04.428
Send him to the mill.

14:04.512 --> 14:07.845
♪ dramatic music  ♪

14:07.929 --> 14:09.845
Thank you all for joining
this emergency assembly

14:09.929 --> 14:11.595
of the Shine-Lucence board.

14:11.679 --> 14:13.387
We are facing a crisis.

14:13.470 --> 14:16.929
As all of you know, we use tin
to produce our solar cells.

14:17.011 --> 14:18.929
It's what makes them
cheaper, safer,

14:19.011 --> 14:21.095
and easier to manufacture
than lead.

14:21.178 --> 14:22.804
[chairman of the board] We
believed that we'd been

14:22.887 --> 14:24.595
[chairman of the board]
sourcing that tin

14:24.679 --> 14:26.095
[chairman of the board] from
safely and humanely run

14:26.178 --> 14:30.136
mines in Australia,
but we just became aware

14:30.220 --> 14:31.970
[chairman of the board] that
a middleman has been

14:32.053 --> 14:33.804
[chairman of the board] selling
suspect tin

14:33.887 --> 14:35.387
[chairman of the board] to
our smelting facility.

14:35.470 --> 14:38.470
Our supply chain Vice President
can tell you more.

14:38.553 --> 14:40.095
I tracked the tin back to here.

14:40.178 --> 14:41.845
Where, exactly, is "here"?
[shouting in distance]

14:41.929 --> 14:44.970
The Congo.
There's militia. With guns.

14:45.053 --> 14:46.679
They're strong-arming people
into the mines.

14:46.762 --> 14:48.595
It's as bad as they say.
Worse...

14:48.679 --> 14:51.053
[door opens]
Shit, I've gotta go--

14:51.136 --> 14:53.679
Allow me to be the one to say
what we're all thinking:

14:53.762 --> 14:55.303
This is  no bueno.

14:55.387 --> 14:57.220
Tin from the Congo
is a conflict mineral.

14:57.303 --> 14:58.679
The mines are controlled by

14:58.762 --> 15:00.762
violent anti-government
warlords.

15:00.845 --> 15:02.387
[chairman of the board] Like
I said: crisis.

15:02.470 --> 15:04.220
[chairman of the board] We'll be
looking to you all

15:04.303 --> 15:06.261
[chairman of the board] for
immediate recommendations...

15:09.762 --> 15:11.470
You know how in Shane--

15:11.553 --> 15:13.679
shit, in every Western
worth its sand--

15:13.762 --> 15:15.845
the main dude can escape,
ride off if he wants,

15:15.929 --> 15:17.720
but then decides
to stay and fight?

15:17.804 --> 15:18.845
I'm Shane?
No. You are not!

15:18.929 --> 15:20.970
You are Mike Prince.
And as your deputy--

15:21.053 --> 15:22.345
Shane wasn't a sheriff.

15:22.428 --> 15:23.970
Yes. I keep meaning
to see that one.

15:24.053 --> 15:25.178
But the point stands.

15:25.261 --> 15:26.679
You ain't sticking around
to fight.

15:26.762 --> 15:28.512
What's recommendation
number two?

15:28.595 --> 15:29.887
There isn't one.

15:30.011 --> 15:31.178
You're supposed to
take recommendation one,

15:31.261 --> 15:32.804
or what the heck
are we doing?

15:32.887 --> 15:34.136
We can't risk
this story breaking

15:34.220 --> 15:35.720
and us still be
in this company.

15:35.804 --> 15:38.887
So you want me to go
Warriors  style.

15:38.970 --> 15:42.095
No. Like I just said, I don't
want you to stay and fight--

15:42.178 --> 15:44.178
No, no, no, like

15:44.261 --> 15:48.470
"Warriors,
come out to play-ay..."

15:48.553 --> 15:51.220
The Warriors
were an unaffiliated

15:51.303 --> 15:53.637
mixed-race street gang
in 1970s New York--

15:53.720 --> 15:55.220
Progressive--

15:55.303 --> 15:57.011
Who got blamed for a murder
they didn't commit.

15:57.095 --> 15:58.762
Caught uptown
in enemy territory,

15:58.845 --> 16:00.845
they had to make their way
back home to Coney Island

16:00.929 --> 16:02.512
with all the other gangs
gunning for 'em.

16:02.595 --> 16:04.720
So they ran.
Or they fought and ran.

16:04.804 --> 16:06.428
How'd I miss
a story like this--

16:06.512 --> 16:07.970
It's a movie.

16:08.053 --> 16:10.387
Damn. Okay.
On my list.

16:10.470 --> 16:13.011
But while fictional
unaffiliated street gangs

16:13.095 --> 16:16.261
may not have any choices,
multibillionaires do.

16:16.345 --> 16:18.512
Not running.

16:18.595 --> 16:20.762
You can find me some
board members to back our play,

16:20.845 --> 16:22.470
but I'm sticking
and turning this around.

16:22.553 --> 16:25.553
♪ dramatic music  ♪

16:25.637 --> 16:28.929
♪♪♪

16:29.011 --> 16:31.679
This company is screwed and our
position right along with it.

16:31.762 --> 16:34.095
Should we come forward
to the press immediately?

16:34.178 --> 16:36.053
Should we dump out?
Or both?

16:36.136 --> 16:38.136
We don't have the benefit
of a track record.

16:38.220 --> 16:39.887
If word of this leaks,
it's a deathblow

16:39.970 --> 16:41.595
to a young firm
with our mission.

16:41.679 --> 16:44.178
In the impact space, I'm not
sure a track record even helps.

16:44.261 --> 16:46.512
Bill McGlashan was the king
of impact investing.

16:46.595 --> 16:49.345
Then Varsity Blues and his head
rolled into a basket.

16:49.428 --> 16:51.762
People are merciless when
it comes to doing good.

16:51.845 --> 16:53.303
And McGlashan
even had Bono.

16:53.387 --> 16:56.679
We need a rockstar
in our corner, too--

16:56.762 --> 16:59.428
Mike Prince.

16:59.512 --> 17:00.970
Go to him.

17:01.053 --> 17:03.470
Enlist him.
Team up.

17:03.553 --> 17:05.428
Together we'll have a better
chance at swaying the board

17:05.512 --> 17:07.428
into doing whatever
you decide is best--

17:07.512 --> 17:09.470
Whoa. Axe would
flip the fuck out.

17:09.553 --> 17:11.220
He almost burst into flames

17:11.303 --> 17:12.845
when he saw Prince at
the Vanity Fair  shoot.

17:12.929 --> 17:15.595
Yes. Their "Fireside Chat"
was Alien vs. Predator.

17:15.679 --> 17:17.804
No fucking fear.

17:17.887 --> 17:20.136
[Lauren] If we win, by making
money, Axe will be happy.

17:20.220 --> 17:24.428
So win, then tell him
how you did it.

17:24.512 --> 17:26.387
♪♪♪

17:26.470 --> 17:27.720
It could work.

17:27.804 --> 17:29.303
It's worth a shot.

17:29.387 --> 17:31.804
But you will
feel his wrath

17:31.887 --> 17:33.804
if we engage with Prince
and make it worse.

17:33.887 --> 17:35.178
Then let's
make it better.

17:35.261 --> 17:37.970
I'll reach out to Scooter
to broker the meeting.

17:38.053 --> 17:41.345
♪♪♪

17:41.428 --> 17:43.011
Let's get active, people!

17:43.095 --> 17:44.845
Traders, you're being
paid to trade.

17:44.929 --> 17:48.095
We're in the moving business,
not the storage business.

17:48.178 --> 17:50.970
So bring me some fucking scalps
for my wall.

17:51.053 --> 17:53.553
Mineral people,
I want exposure.

17:53.637 --> 17:55.011
Yesterday.

17:55.095 --> 17:58.095
Get me longer than
the Hunt Brothers in 1980!

17:58.178 --> 18:00.595
We've gotta grab the rock,
bring back the shiny shit.

18:00.679 --> 18:04.345
Um, I'd like to join in the
zesty and aggressive approach.

18:04.428 --> 18:06.804
But I've got to say: I'm not
sure what we're supposed to do.

18:06.887 --> 18:08.762
Okay. Come on. Come on.
Come on. Come on.

18:08.845 --> 18:11.178
You guys are running last gen.
I need you next gen.

18:11.261 --> 18:13.095
Victor!

18:13.178 --> 18:15.178
Purely optional.

18:15.261 --> 18:17.887
But for those of you who are
ready to cross the threshold

18:17.970 --> 18:19.470
and become a version of himself

18:19.553 --> 18:21.553
with the energy
of a 17-year-old,

18:21.637 --> 18:22.929
the focus of a 30-year-old

18:23.011 --> 18:25.387
and the wisdom of
a 100-year-old,

18:25.470 --> 18:27.387
step the fuck up.

18:29.804 --> 18:33.303
Let me tell you:
I have never felt so focused,

18:33.387 --> 18:36.136
and with all of you at the
same level on this v-shit,

18:36.220 --> 18:39.887
I think we're looking at
85% returns on the week,

18:39.970 --> 18:41.470
to say nothing
of the quarter.

18:41.553 --> 18:42.887
Sounds good, Axe.

18:42.970 --> 18:44.011
Give me a few of those
Major League beans

18:44.095 --> 18:45.929
for the Mase Carb crew.

18:46.011 --> 18:47.053
Whew.

18:47.136 --> 18:49.970
FDA approval
pending...?

18:50.053 --> 18:51.887
Oh God,
I don't want diarrhea,

18:51.970 --> 18:54.929
involuntary muscle spasms,
psychotic delusions--

18:55.011 --> 18:58.261
It says "in rare cases,"
you fucking baby.

18:58.345 --> 18:59.679
I'm in.

18:59.762 --> 19:01.929
♪ up-tempo music  ♪

19:02.011 --> 19:03.762
[exhales sharply]

19:03.845 --> 19:06.637
Fine. But I'm gonna
need some water.

19:06.720 --> 19:09.470
